A smartphone tracking firm helping Donald Trump clinch his 2020 presidential reelection recently told investors it’s identified a promising new profit opportunity: the global coronavirus pandemic.
“Beyond identifying coveted voters, mobile data can also be used to define ad targeting parameters with incredible accuracy,” reads a section of Phunware’s site that compares the buying and selling of personal data to the 1849 Gold Rush.
The company’s privacy policy grants the company license to use personal data for essentially whatever purposes it deems necessary for however long it deems necessary.
“Mobile data brokers, who claim to have data on the movements of everyone, are mostly overselling their capabilities.
But when we are talking public health, potential law enforcement, and employment, these companies’ mistakes can be catastrophic.”